title: 3. Sue Raw. Soundbite. Wedding and a baby

description:
Transcript:
“The first time he came to the house to pick me up, in those days it was quite fashionable to wear black shirts and white ties, and he came in looking quite Jack-the-Lad, and my mother just rolled her eyes. She did say to me afterwards, “I thought ‘oh no, who the hell is she bringing home now?’” [Laughs]. But she actually, very, very quickly, fell in love with this guy, unlike my first husband. She had never, never approved of him or the way his family lived their lives. It wasn’t how she was brought up and she didn't want it for me, but I was 18 and I thought I knew everything, thought I had the answers. And I’m now nearly 68 and I still don’t have all the answers. [Laughs].”

title: 2. Sue Raw. Soundbite. Mothers' Approval

description:
Transcript:
“Its 26 years since Alan died, this year. For probably about 16 of those years, maybe more, I was quite happy to just dodge along. There was nobody else in my life, no partner, but there were times when the girls used to say, “Well, Mum, you’re a bit young, should you not …?” I was quite happy doing what I was doing. But anyway, against my better judgment, I let them talk me into joining Match.com, and so I did meet one chap, called Bob, who I thought it was going okay and then realised that my pensions were the attraction, rather than me, so that didn't last too long. 

Then Ron got in touch with me, and that would be possibly eight years ago now. He had a lot of service in the military. He’s never served as a regular, but he's been a reservist for many years and involved with the military for many, many years. He retired as a Major and was still working for the Ministry of Defence, actually, when I met him, as kind of the liaison officer between reservists and employers. [...]  we wrote to each other for a while and then we met and would go out maybe every two or three weeks for dinner or something like that. Then we were talking about holidays one time, and he said, “If ever you need a holiday, somebody to go on holiday with …“  
Because one thing, I did go on singles holidays! I’ve been to China on my own. I’ve been to Italy on my own. But it’s not always easy, so he did say, “If you ever want a chum to go on holiday with, just let me know.”  [...]  And there were one or two other things that happened that year that kind of made me … Because I’ve always tried to live by the philosophy that life’s too short, so to grab it … I mean, that was one of the last things that my husband said on the Wednesday before he died. He died on the Saturday, and he said, “Sue, if you want it, get it. If you want to go somewhere or do something, do it, because you can’t take it where I’m going.” And I’ve always tried to remember that but you know, sometimes you can tend to take it for granted and it goes past. But there’d been one or two things and I thought … I knew that Ron was just waiting for me to say the word. So I phoned Helen first and she said, “Oh Mum, just do it. Just do it. Stop it,” you know. 

So I phoned Ron, because I think I’d just seen him the night before, or we’d just had the conversation that day or something, so I phoned him and said, “Alright then, how do you fancy that holiday?” I think he was like, “What?” I think I took the wind out of his sails. [Laughs]. So anyway, we decided we would try a week first in Tunisia and see how that went, and that was in February 2015 – four years ago. And we’ve kind of been partners since. We don’t live together. I think we’re both too independent. I certainly am. I’m quite happy that he’s got his place in Carnoustie and I’ve got my place here. He comes here and stays sometimes, and I go there and stay sometimes, and we go on holidays together and we speak every day [...] it works for us. It works for us. But I’ve been Sue Raw for 45 years now; I shall be Sue Raw when I die.”

title: 19. Sue Raw. New relationships

description:
Transcript:
“... it’s always been important to me to acknowledge my father and my other male relatives’ contribution, and yes, since then, for Alan. It’s important to us as military people to be, you know, just to say thank you to those that are still prepared to serve and still prepared to make that sacrifice if they’re called on to do so. So yes, Remembrance is hugely important, hugely important. I will not go out of the house, from the day that poppies go on sale until the day after Remembrance, I will not go out of the house unless I’m wearing a poppy.”

title: 18. Sue Raw. Remembrance

description:
Transcript:
“I did say to Helen that I thought at first, when he died, on the day he died, I said, “Try to see this as he is letting you know how important this day was to him in his life, not because it's the day of his death. He is going on the day that was most important to him in his life, when he first became a father.” So I think she's seen it mostly like that. What we did, I mean, when the girls were still at home for the first few years we would ... In the morning, we would go to the crematorium or we’d do the flowers or we’d do whatever, and then after that, it's, “Right, we’ve done that. It’s Helen’s birthday. Above all, anything else, May 29th is Helen’s birthday.” We acknowledge his death, we acknowledge the anniversary, but it's Helen's birthday.”

title: 17. Sue Raw. Daughter's birthday, husband's death day

description:
Transcript:
“Birthdays, it depends. We try to get together on each other's birthdays, but it doesn’t always work but … [coughs]. Excuse me. It just so happens, this Sunday, we’re all getting together because it's Stewart's birthday. Helen’s had a couple of her birthdays away when she was on ships and things. Alan’s birthday, we tend to celebrate in our own way. I usually get flowers for the house, and we do have a memorial plaque in the Garden of Remembrance at the crematorium.”

title: 16. Sue Raw. Soundbite. Anniversaries

description:
Transcript:
“Initially, I think I dealt with it quite well. I did get lots of books from organisations. There was on that I found particularly helpful called, Grief Through the Bereavement Journey. And I think I was concentrating on the girls. Catherine, particularly, because she was still at school. [Pause]. I think it was about … You know, when it really hit me, was about five years after he died. I think you concentrate, the first year, on … And I did read in one of these books that the second year is the worst, then I thought ‘I can’t see how that’s the case’ but it’s true in reality, or for me, it was. The first year, you concentrate on getting over the first birthdays, the first Christmas, the first wedding anniversary - the first of everything. But when you start doing everything for the second time, that’s when it hits you that this is forever now. This is forever, he’s not going to be here. That’s when it really started to hit home, I think.

But it was after … I think I’d got to about five years when I started to have panic attacks. I had a crippling, crippling depression. It was dizzy spells, and I just felt unwell, I just felt really, really unwell, and I went to see Alan Cochrane, who was our GP and who, as I said to you, was just wonderful when Alan was dying. He is just a typical GP and I’m just so sad that he’s retired. But I went to see him, and he said, “This was always going to happen.” He said, “Sometimes it happens with people earlier, but you’ve gone on …” Because I did see him quite regularly because I’m asthmatic, so I do have to go for checkups. He said, “New bathroom, new kitchen, you’ve had all these projects …” [...] And this is what my GP said; “You’ve kept yourself busy with all these projects,” and he said, “But now you haven’t got a project so now you have to sit and grieve. Now you have to sit and think about what you’ve lost.” So I did go through a terrible bout of depression about five years afterwards that I was on medication … I think I was off work for about a month. I was on medication for perhaps a couple of years.”

title: 15. Sue Raw. Soundbite. Dealing with grief - physical

description:
Transcript:
“I think it was some time before I realised ... I didn’t even know about the War Widows’ Association for quite some time, and when I did, I didn’t join because I didn't think I really was a ‘war widow.’ [...] Because, I guess, for me, a war widow, and I suppose for most people, a war widow is somebody whose husband or partner, wife, whatever, has been killed in conflict. And Alan had not died in conflict, although he had given his entire adult life in service to his country. But when we got the award letter, when he got the award letter as a war pensioner, the Ministry of Defence were quite … There was no pussyfooting around, it was just, “Yes, we are responsible, because we sent him out to hot countries and …” In fact, when Alan used to serve in places like the Far East and the Mediterranean and, you know, when he was on ships that went out there, they were actually expected to wander around on deck without their shirts on and exposed to that kind of risk. [...]

... actually, yes, my husband is dead because of his naval service. Just because he didn’t die in a conflict doesn’t make his death any less traumatic for his family and for us. We’ve lost him. Because he wouldn’t have done some of the things he did that maybe contributed to his death if he hadn’t been in the Navy. But I did struggle with that for a while, I didn’t really think I was a war widow.”

title: 14. Sue Raw. Soundbite. Being a 'war widow'

description:
Transcript:
“... you know, we do deserve better treatment, we do deserve to be recognised that we did give a lot of our lives supporting our partners whilst they serve their Queen and country. Alan always used to call her “the boss”, the Queen, if he saw her on the telly; “Oh, it’s the boss.” But yes, I do think … At the time, you got on with it, but on reflection, I don't think our contribution then was acknowledged as much as maybe it is now, and I still don’t  think it's enough now. I don't think military families are valued as much as they should be. Because if it wasn't for the family supporting these men and women at home and giving them some sense of normality outside of the military, they wouldn’t be able to serve in the way that they do, I don't think.”

title: 13. Sue Raw. Soundbite. Recognition of the roles of miltary wives and families

description:
Transcript:
“Yes, we had lots of support, lots of support. But if you're asking me about the military? Then no. Other than the forms, you know, that you get from the Ministry of Defence and that kind of thing. I had no visits from the military. From some of Alan’s former shipmates, yes, but not formally from the military. [...]  I think it was probably a case of, “Well, he’s a civilian now.” Yes. So it might have been very different. I can’t say I’m critical of them for that.”

title: 12. Sue Raw. Soundbite. Support from the military

description:
Transcript:
“Support from friends and family, it was just, it was just second to none. My employer, I cannot speak highly enough of my employer. My manager at that time, just … I had actually been on sick leave from Alan becoming unable to walk and unable to do very much for himself in the January, and I didn't go back to work once that happened, once he lost the use of his legs. My GP was brilliant, he gave me a sick line and he put, I think he put, I think he put “stress and anxiety” or something like that. I said, “But I’m not really ill …” He said, “Sue, you will be ill if you go to work and you have to leave him here in the care of somebody else,” he said, “So we’re going to sign you off as well.” And my manager was absolutely wonderful, she just used to phone and say, “Sue, you’re going to need another sick line, so-and-so, whenever it runs out.” They even … While he was ill at one point, when we were going through the really critical part of his illness, they organised a rota with my colleagues, and they used to come and take me to the hospital and wait for us, so I didn’t have the stress of driving. 

And afterwards, it was just, if I didn't feel like working a whole day, I didn’t work a whole day it was just; I did what I felt like. My employer was, as I say, just second to none. Fife Council is just a brilliant employer, even now. They have been a brilliant, supportive employer.”

title: 11. Sue Raw. Soundbite. Support from work

description:
Transcript:
“And then I met Alan, I met my sailor. It wasn't the most romantic of meetings. I had gone out for a night out with my friend, my divorce proceedings were in progress by then. I had gone out with my friend, and we’d gone to a nightclub, and he was sitting opposite me across the room and he just happened to catch my eye, and when the music started, and a nod of his head – did I want to go up and dance? And that was it. So yes, when he told me he was in the Navy, I thought ‘ah …’ [Sighs]. It was a bit of a ‘heart-sink’ moment after my experience with my first husband in the Army, but … 
However, we spent the rest of the evening together and then he was home on leave, and we went out two or three times. We went out for drinks, went out for meals, and then we just kind of fell into a pattern that whenever he was home on leave, we would get together and have a night out or a meal or whatever, or a day out, a trip here and a trip there.”

title: 1. Sue Raw. Soundbite. First Meeting: I met my sailor

description:
Transcript:
“But I remember the day that the guy came to do another assessment, because we had to contact them every time there had been a change in his illness, the GP had just left, Alan Cochrane had just left, and he was in bed. As he was leaving, I think he was going back into hospital that night, he said, “Sue, he’s going to have to go back into hospital.” He said, “There is nothing I can do for him,” and he used the phone, and he said, “They’ll be here soon.” And I just looked at him and I said, “He hasn’t got long now, has he?” [Pause]. And he said [Sobs] … My GP went away crying. He just gave me a cuddle, he couldn't speak, and he just went away crying. And then the doctor appointed by the Ministry of Defence came in after that, and he just ... I said, “We’re waiting for an ambulance, actually, to take him back into the Western General,” and he said, “Well, I am obliged.” I said, “I know, I know. Please go upstairs,” and he went upstairs, into the bedroom, and he just turned around and came out, and just said, “It’ll be one hundred per cent.” Then he died, I think, about six weeks after that, on 29th May, which was Helen's 19th birthday.”

title: 10. Sue Raw. Soundbite. Being assessed for War Pension eligibility (Disablement)

description:
Transcript:
“Well I was eight months pregnant and very pleased that I was pregnant, even though it was unexpected and I was sat knitting in the front garden. We didn't have a back garden because it was like a back to back but it was a huge house. And, I was sat knitting baby clothes when this car pulled up outside and these two policemen got out and looked at me because I was eight months pregnant, said, "Is your dad in?" and I had to say, "My father has died but my mother is in," so they went and rang the bell. I thought they looked at me strange when they came back out after a few minutes and then my mother said – came to the door and said that, "I think you should come in, I've got something to tell you." And it was just a piece of paper that said that they were sorry to say that he'd been killed in Korea. And that was the 24th May which was a spring Bank - they used to call it Whit Sunday. And she broke the news to me that Roy had been killed but you can't come to terms when there's no body. So I was eight months pregnant, so it wasn't a nice period that, no.”

About the interview:
Kathleen shares her life story, including the loss of her husband Roy during the Korean War. She was eight months pregnant with their child when he was killed. Kathleen describes growing up in the Huddersfield area of West Yorkshire during the inter-war years. She recalls meeting her husband, courting, and their frugal wedding in 1951. Kathleen recounts her treatment as a young widow and mother and talks about her second marriage, her pilgrimage to Korea, and her recent efforts to have her first husband's name commemorated locally. The interview was conducted by Nadine Muller on 13th November 2018.
title: Kathleen Cockcroft. Soundbite. Describes being told the news of her husband's death

description:
Transcript:
“They didn't go with phones like they do nowadays when they join the Army and they keep in touch. You were lucky to get a letter, and you were - half of it had been blacked out. And the next I knew, I found out I was pregnant. It must have happened when I went to the Passing-Out Parade. And, so he knew I was having a baby but we didn't know the sex in those days. And, I chose the first name which was Robert and he chose the second name which was Gary. And I gave birth after he'd been killed. I was eight months pregnant. And unfortunately, at seven months, I lost my father. He died. My mother and I were widowed within a month of each other.”

description:
Transcript:
“I know that he played football and we'd only just met and he’d said where they were going to play and I'd made a point of saying I'd go to watch. He had broken his leg and he sort of made his way, under great difficulties, because he said he'd see me. I think he was frightened that if he didn't turn up, he would be history. [Laughs] But he was a kind boy.”

title: Kathleen Cockcroft. Soundbite. First Date

description:
Transcript:
“It, it also hurt that there was nowhere local, I mean we have a lovely park, Greenhead Park. It has a lovely memorial area flagged with pillars up and there isn't one person's name there that has died for the country there. And there was nowhere that had his name. He just didn't exist. So for years I kept asking people, British Legion and other people. No, they couldn't do anything. Then unfortunately, my husband had had a bad stroke and went into a nursing home. And I felt awful doing it, but I was 82 and I - it still rankled that my husband had given his life and nowhere was his name in Huddersfield. So I went and knocked on the vicar's door of the church where my husband had grown up and gone to school, and they went from the school to the church for services. And there was this very nice lady who was in the middle of bathing child, a baby, came down and talked to me. She put the wheels in motion of having his name at the church. So after – and a councillor called Terry White, he did a lot to help me. He took over and the British Legion, at last, took notice but it was me that knocked on the door and said, "My husband has given his life for his country, this is the church where he went to, and I would like his name."”

title: Kathleen Cockcroft. Soundbite. "Holiday, it was a pilgrimage" Kathleen recalls her trip to Korea

description:
Transcript:
“R: So times were hard because, I think I got £6 a week to live on. That was for me and the baby. 
I: Was that your husband's pension? 
R: No, a war pension. I mean it was a pittance and after a few weeks I did arrange to see someone and it was a room full of men sat round a table. They took one look at me and they said, "How old are you? Oh, you're young enough to get married again. You need to go to work. You can go to work." I had a six week old baby and I was told to go to work. And I went to work. And I said, I never got any extra money. They said I had to earn it. And I did go, I think my baby was about five months old and I said I would never ask for another ha’penny if I starved.”

description:
Transcript:
“But when you remarried in those days, if you were living with anyone, they stopped your pension. And if you remarried, you had to inform them and they stopped your pension but they kept on, it was something like £2.50 a week for my child. My husband never actually adopted him, but he brought him up. So, the pension stopped when I remarried. But it certainly isn't like it is now, but we won't go into that because I don't want to sound bitter.”

title: Kathleen Cockcroft. Soundbite. Losing the War Widows' Pension on remarriage

description:
Transcript:
“Part of me thinks you've got a new life and that's part of your old life, but I have – I can say this, can't I? – I was told years ago by somebody whose husband died as a result of the injuries that he got during the war, much to my amazement, it all depends what it says on their death certificate. She has got … Bless her, she's dead now herself. She got the War Widows’ Pension. So I kept – I didn't tell my husband these thoughts I was having because he had quite a lot wrong with him over the years – I kept that in mind. So when my husband died, which will be four years in February, without a great deal of fuss, I put the wheels in motion to apply for it. There was no problem with that because, with me already having had it, it wasn't something new I was going to get. I have [it] now instead of the state pension. It isn't a lot more, but it is. You don’t tax it – it's tax free, so that is a big thing. So, it was like, it was reinstated. I'd stopped having it, and now I'm having it. So I suppose as well, my age, perhaps they think they wouldn't be paying it very long. [Laughs]”

description:
Transcript:
“I was in labour and this nurse came to the bed. Or was it after she'd been born? "What have you been doing for five years?" said she, because there was five years between my son [and daughter]. I said, "Well, as a matter of fact, I was widowed." You know, they're so flippant sometimes and so judgemental. She was an Irish lady and as far as they were concerned there was no such thing as contraception in those days. So that more or less … "What did you want me to be doing?" People assume, if they see somebody with one child, "Oh, you've only one child." That person could have lost a child, which happens. You know, I know someone, and it would have been so easy for me to say, "Oh, only one child." She'd had a child and that child had died. So you have to be careful what you say to people.”

About the interview:

title: Kathleen Cockcroft. Soundbite. On people making hurtful assumptions

description:
Transcript:
“Well, to start with, they don't like speaking to you. It's the same now. If you lose someone, they don't know what to say. And you get yourself pointed out. I got off the bus and, of course, I'm out here [heavily pregnant], which it didn't say in the paper. There was no big article. It was just in death column. I'd taken that down myself. I got off this bus, and I saw these three turn round and point to me. So, they – wherever they lived further up – they must have said, "There's somebody further down that's been widowed," and suddenly they look at you: "You're pregnant." So they don't really know how to treat you. And it isn't that they're being cold or anything. It's just they don't know how to treat you. I've seen people cross over the road sooner than come up to you. Then I took my son – I think he would be about two – and I took him to see a friend that had moved down south, on the train. This lady – it was when they had compartments and you sat opposite each other – and they were smiling at him and said something about his daddy. So I just said, "Well, I'm sorry, but ...", and then I just told a brief version, "You have upset me," she said. I thought, "You asked. What do you want me to say, that he's got a daddy? He hasn't got a daddy." You know, and so, it either – how can I put this? – I don't want to make it sound bitter. I don't. I've said that before. It makes you strong. You either go under, or you start swimming and you survive, and I survived. So on the whole, I was self-supporting because I'm that sort of a person.”

description:
Transcript:
“I've been to the Arboretum and that is a beautiful place, I'd love to go again. I saw his name and it was there. So …  And, it's a lovely place because – I don't know whether you've been or not, they're not captains, they're not colonels, they're not sergeants, they're all the same. They're human beings. And there was his name up with everybody else's. It's in … in the days they died, each one, you know. That's how they do it. But what upset me was the amount of space they'd left for future deaths and already there's another couple of columns got added names. But it's a beautiful place. It was very moving when we went there.”

description:
Transcript:
“Well the first or second year it got to me and I felt I had to speak to the vicar. I met her at a later date on the street, and I said to her, "Excuse me, but in your service on Sunday, you never once mentioned Korea." I said, "It's the Forgotten War." It's known as the Forgotten War. I said, "But my husband gave his life. He's buried in Korea," and since then, that is added to all these extra places where people have given their lives now, whereas as far as some people are concerned, there's just been two wars, the First World War and the Second World War.”

description:
Transcript:
“But it is hard when you're trying to bring a child up now, then, in those days, because I can remember being worried about him at one stage and taking him to the local clinic, which is now no longer there, and being sort of accused of being highly strung. You know, "You're worrying unnecessarily. There's nothing wrong with your child," and sent on my bike again so to speak and then having an apology because they'd looked at my record or what and suddenly realised I was a widow, and only me to look after this tiny baby, responsible for one. Then when I did remarry, people can be hurtful. I had some hurtful things said when I was on my way to the nursery with him, by people stood in a queue and assumed that you were going out for pocket money and things like that, and you're actually going out to pay the rent.”

description:
Transcript:
“Very frugal actually, because we weren't earning big money and war was on so people gave me their coupons to go and get an outfit. It wasn't a white dress. It was a very nice dress. I think it was a greyish blue. It had a little hat. And we got married in church. And unfortunately we couldn't afford the organ, so it was ‘clip, clop, clip, clop’ with my heels all the way down on my father's arm. So … Then we came out and you just went somewhere local which was opposite the church and had a ham tea with trifle, things like that and a cake. Couldn't afford a honeymoon. [Laughs] So, yes. But then we weren't married long then when he was called. We were living in a one up and one down.”

description:
Transcript:
“But I think what hurt about being widowed was when I went to the park with, with him in the pram and the daddies were playing with the children, that, that did hurt. But I always said I wasn't the first and I wouldn't be the last to be widowed and it's still happening. Yes. But I was, for years, upset that he'd given his life for his country. But, it still rankled that it was National Service he was doing. He didn't want to go in the Army and be a soldier. And, and that is what hurt most.”

description:
Transcript:
“He wasn't a man that asked you questions or talked about things, you know, so this is probably why I didn't explore things sooner because he was my husband. But I think when we were first married, you sort of, not have nightmares, but start dreaming during the night. I dreamt that he hadn't died and that I had to choose between them and things like that. It can be upsetting because you've left one life behind, but it's still with you. So, you've got to adjust to realising that it isn't going to happen. I mean, it is a big thing to take on somebody with a child, isn't it? I mean they do it now all the time, don't they, but they didn't in those days. People brought up children on their own. So, I mean I was married to Roy in 1951 and he was killed in '53. 
And, he'd been away from the November when he went and caught this ship, and killed in the May, so he'd been abroad six months. I'd been working and leading a life, and he was the other side of the world, so I'd already started living my life on my own, as it was. And then, you see, and then I was married to Peter for … I was 26 when I married Peter. So, I mean, we'd been married nearly 58 years when he died. So, I'd had a lot longer with Peter than I’d had … I've lived my life with Peter, haven't I? So, you've got a life and you live it the best way that you can.”

description:
Transcript:
“Went in to do his National Service. He chose the Army because he said the Air Force was three years and he would be out quicker, in two. So he went in the Army and went to Richmond into the Green Howards and did his ‘square bashing.’ And then he did the Passing out Parade, which I went to by myself. Then we - he came out and before you knew what was happening, he was in the Duke of Wellingtons then. He'd come home on leave prior to being, what was the word for it, vacation. And he went on this boat and that's where he learnt to fight. I'd never heard of Korea, didn't know where Korea was but we were fighting with the United Nations. And he was taught to fight, so I was told, on the boat going over because all they'd done at Richmond was square bashing, "Do as you’re told, you're in the Army."”

description: Elaine was born and raised in Margate in Kent. She was engaged to be married to Lieutenant Marc Lawrence, who served in the Royal Navy’s Fleet Air Arm and died in a helicopter collision in the North Arabian Gulf in 2003. Elaine explains her position as a fiance, rather than a wife, whereby she had to prove she had a ‘significant and long-term relationship’ with Marc before the Royal Navy would grant her his service pension, even though she was listed by Marc as his next of kin. Elaine was not deemed eligible to receive a War Widows’ Pension as they were not married. Elaine talks about her childhood, her education, her long distance courtship with Marc, how she coped with his death, and her life as a successful business woman running a consultancy company with her husband. Elaine was interviewed by Melanie Bassett on 6 December 2018.
title: An interview with Elaine Gosden

description:
Ruth Maxwell recounts the affect of the loss of her father John Maxwell to herself, her brother, and her mother. She describes how her parents were deeply in love and how her mother Joyce coped with the grief in everyday life.

Transcript:
So, Mum was very young, she was 26 when all this happened, and she was obviously very much in love with my father. Because they'd only been married for five years and they'd had this incredibly whirlwind romance. And she was as traumatised as I was, not to mention my brother. I’ve got no idea what effect it had on my brother because, well, that’s another story that I might talk about later. She kept it all battened down, the grief and the bereavement. She said that she would wake up in the morning and her pillow would be soaking wet from tears. But during the day we never saw it. She obviously just had to put it to one side and get on.
title: Ruth Maxwell_Soundbite_Mothers love and loss of husband

description:
Christina Claypole describes how her parents, Christiane and John Kirton, started courting at an early age.

Transcript:
I know that my dad courted my mum from when she was fourteen, still at school. I’ve got a letter that said that he loved her in her little white ankle socks, and he used to pick her up on a motorbike from school. And I think they were married at seventeen and had two babies very quickly.
title: Christina Claypole_Soundbite_Parents Courting

description:
Bernice Bartlett describes a poem sent be her late husband Harry Golding when stationed at Anzio, Italy, during World War Two. Harry was killed in Italy in 1944. 

Transcript:
R: No. I’ve only kept one letter. I went into hospital, and I got rid of all my letters. I didn’t want anyone else to read them. I kept one, yes. 

 I: Just for you.   
                                                           
R: Just for me. One. The one with the poem he wrote. I don’t know where that is. He wrote a poem he had done about Anzio. The last words were, “once a year at Anzio time” … something … . “Remember once a year at Anzio time, the one I love so dear”, or something to those words. 

 I: That’s lovely. 

 R: It was lovely.
title: Bernice Bartlett_Soundbite_In Anzio Time

description:
Jeannie Benjamin describes how she found out in her mothers' memoir how her mother had fallen in love with her father. 

Her father, Eric Benjamin, died during World War Two, leaving wife Betty with Jeannie (18 months) and her younger sister (3 weeks).

Transcript:
And then she met my father in 1937, and she writes in her little, few pieces of paper, how that, when she first saw him, he was striding down Teddington High Street in his Sea Scout uniform, looking all fit and scrubbed and tanned, and immediately fell in love with him. That was quite romantic, really.
title: Jeannie Benjamin_Soundbite First Meeting Of Her Parents

description:
Patricia Anne Rickwood remembers finding her mother's last letters to her father, which were sent back after he died in the Second World War.

Transcript:
I also have the last two letters that Mum wrote to him that were sent back when he died. The tone of them both is just how much they love each other. They're incredibly repetitive about just how they love and miss each other and how much they're looking forward to when the war will be over. Then once I'd come on the scene, how much my father was going to enjoy looking after me. All very terribly sentimental by modern standards, but they don't give a lot of information. They're just very love letters. They wrote every day to each other, but much the same thing.
title: Patricia Anne Rickwood_Soundbite_Parents' Letters
Soundbite. Wendy Hutchinson. "You're a war widow forever."

description:
Christina talks about not knowing life any differently than without a father, and how her mother made up for the absence of a father.

You can listen to, read, and download Christina's full interview here: http://www.warwidowsstories.org.uk/stories/an-interview-with-christina-claypole/.
title: WWSCC Soundbite I Lost My Dad But I Had A Wonderful Mother

description: In this soundbite Sylvia Elliott recalls the difficult years after Bill, her first husband, was demobilized from the British Army due to an injury he sustained in Korea. He was unaware of his entitlement to an army pension, and the family lived without any financial support for seventeen years, until he eventually started receiving his pension.
title: Soundbite. Sylvia Elliott. ‘[W]e Had To Live From Hand To Mouth On What We Got.’

description: In this soundbite Sylvia Elliott describes her earliest memories of her childhood during the Second World War. Sylvia was evacuated to Stanley Common, just outside Derby, and recalls feeling bewildered about the separation from her parents, but her fond memories of picking tomatoes in the summer and going ice-skating on the village pond in the winter.
title: Soundbite. Sylvia Elliott. Earliest Memories

description: In this soundbite, Joan describes her decision to change careers. As a young war widow and single mother to David in her twenties, she had had to leave her career in nursing, and return to work as a typist for in the civil service to make ends meet. After her son David went to university, she decided “Right, now it’s my turn”, and retrained to become a teacher through the City Literary Institute and Battersea College of Education in London.
title: Soundbite. Joan Eggmore. “Right, Now It’s My Turn.”

description: Joan Eggmore recalls her difficult financial situation after the death of her husband Dougie, who passed away shortly after the end of the Second World War as a result of his service: ‘as you can imagine, it was difficult enough keeping myself because I knew absolutely nothing about applying for a War Widows’ Pension. Nobody ever mentioned it anywhere.’
title: Soundbite. Joan Eggmore. “I Knew Absolutely Nothing About Applying For A War Widows’ Pension.”

description: Ruth describes her mother’s involvement with the founding of the War Widows Association and their fight to end the taxation of war widows’ pensions: ‘a group of war widows managed to galvanise themselves, in about 1969, I think, and met in London in a Lyons Corner House. I don’t know whereabouts in London, but Mum was one of them.’
title: Soundbite. Ruth Maxwell. “[T]hey Were Just A Disparate Group Of Women, Standing Up For Their Rights”

description: In this soundbite Ruth recalls the moment she discovered that her mother Joyce had kept every letter she had exchanged with her husband, William, during the war, which documented their entire courtship, from when they first met at the Ashridge Convalescent Home in 1945, to their preparations for marriage. She describes their very first exchange, in which William asked Joyce to meet him for drink next time he was on leave in London. Her response was, “Well, you could have knocked me down with a feather”, and so they arranged to meet.
title: Soundbite. Ruth Maxwell. “Well, You Could Have Knocked Me Down With A Feather”

description: In this soundbite Mary recalls feeling concerned that her husband’s funeral would attract political attention, after he was killed in 1988 nine days before Christmas, during the Troubles in Norther Ireland: “I know this is a public event, but it has to be private for the children, and the children have to be protected. The whole way through it, I mean, that was your focus. The children.”
title: Soundbite. Mary Moreland. Politicians

description: Mary describes the moment she found out about her husband’s death and recalls her initial reaction: ‘I thought I was probably very coherent. Hindsight, I probably wasn’t, but at the time I thought I was thinking very clearly. I remember the secretary making tea. It’s funny the little things that you remember because I said, “No, could I have a cup of coffee?” because I don’t drink tea. I think they were like, “No, tea for shock”. I’m like, “No, I like coffee”. So I had my cup of coffee […].'
title: Soundbite. Mary Moreland. “No, Tea For Shock”

description: Anne describes the remembrance events she attended with her mum, including the tree they had planted in memory of her dad at the National Memorial Arboretum, “a great big Lombardy poplar in a road called Yeomanry Avenue, which is the one that commemorates the Battle of Arnhem”.
title: Soundbite. Patricia Anne Rickwood. A Tree at The National Memorial Arboretum

description: Anne describes her attempts to find out more about her father, and the idealised picture her mother painted of him after his death at the Battle of Arnhem during the Second World War
title: Soundbite. Patricia Anne Rickwood.  "I've Never Met Anyone Really Who Knew Him".

description: Rita Armin explains how her husband, Henry, a veteran of the Second World War, ends up in a wheelchair after an unsuccessful operation, and how their son, Philip, helped care for his father.
title: Soundbite. Rita Armin on Her Son Helping to Care For His Father.
Rita Armin. "Story of Two People". 27 February 2017.

description: Joan Eggmore met her husband, Dougie, in London after the war, and they had one son, David, before Dougie passed away as a result of his service. Joan talks about their courtship and wedding day, about Dougie’s role as a draughtsman in India and Burma, and about his chronic health condition which was exacerbated by his service. She describes her early working life, including in the fur department in Harrods and as a staff nurse, and outlines how she went back to education in her forties to train as a teacher. Joan details the social and financial challenges of being a widow, including her application for a War Widows’ Pension.
title: An Interview with Joan Eggmore. Conducted by Jeannie Benjamin. 17 March 2017.

description: Bernice Bartlett talks about meeting and marrying her husband Harry Golding aged seventeen. She remembers how Harry was reluctant to join the Army as he did not want to leave Bernice and their first born son, Bernard, and how Harry never met their second son, Barry, born in 1943. Bernice talks about living in Maidstone with her mother (also a widow) during the war, and recounts the day she received the letter telling her that Harry had been killed by a booby trap near Florence in Italy, as well as visiting his grave 40 years after Harry’s death. Bernice describes her life running country pubs with her second husband, her large family, including four children, eight grandchildren, eleven great-grandchildren and one great-great-grandchild, and her many hobbies, including playing bridge and whist.
title: An Interview with Bernice Bartlett. Conducted by Nadine Muller. 12 May 2017.

description: Ruth Maxwell’s parents, Joyce and William, met in Ashridge Convalescent Home in 1945 – Joyce recovering from suspected TB and William as a repatriated Prisoner of War. Ruth details the circumstances of William’s death as a result of renal failure in 1950, leaving Joyce with two young children and pregnant with their third child. Joyce was a founding member of the War Widows’ Association and Ruth describes her mother as a spirited, determined woman who established her own typing business to support the family. Ruth reflects on how the death of her father has impacted her throughout her life.
title: An Interview with Ruth Maxwell. Conducted by Nadine Muller. 8 May 2017.

description: Jeannie Benjamin recounts the story of her mother Margaret Benjamin who was widowed when her husband (Jeannie’s father) Eric Benjamin was killed in action during the Second World War. Margaret was left with two young daughters, Jeannie aged 18 months, and Sally, just three weeks old. Jeannie describes her parents’ loving relationship and shares letters and poems written by her father, as well as extracts from her mother’s memoir. She remembers her mother as a strong, lively personality who profoundly influenced Jeannie’s development as a feminist and an activist. Jeannie reflects on the impact of losing her father as a young child and the processes of recovering his memory in later life through researching and writing a book.
title: An Interview with Jeannie Benjamin. Conducted by Nadine Muller. 24 July 2017.

description: Anne Rickwood’s father, Gordon, was killed in the Battle of Arnhem during the Second World War, leaving behind Anne’s mother, Patricia Starr Vicary, with a small baby. Anne describes her mother’s precarious financial situation and the challenges she faced as a war widow. Anne talks about her own awareness of her father’s death and how it impacted on her mother. She outlines how she visits Arnhem on an annual basis, and explains the importance of National Memorial Arboretum as a space of commemoration for her mother.
title: An Interview with Patricia Anne Rickwood. Conducted by Nadine Muller. 22 May 2017.

description: Sylvia Elliott talks about her childhood in Derby during the Second World War and about meeting her husband. Bill, who had been badly injured in Korea. She describes her forty year marriage to Bill, their two daughters, Carol and Dawn, and his commitment to the British Legion. Sylvia outlines her life since Bill’s death, including moving to Skegness, travelling around the world, and marrying again to her second husband, John. Sylvia also details the difficulties she encountered applying for a War Widow’s Pension.
title: An Interview with Sylvia Elliott. Conducted by Mrs Glenda Spacey. 10 May 2017.

description: Christina Claypole was born in South Shields, and was evacuated as a child during the Second World War to Upton with her brother Ron and her mother, Christiane Kirton, who was widowed in 1942. Christina’s father John was killed when the submarine HMS Olympus was blown up in Malta. Christina describes life as an evacuee, and remembers her happy childhood despite her mother’s financial struggles. She recalls taking her mother to visit Malta and lay a wreath in the ocean, and describes her mother’s active life as a widow, including a visit to Buckingham Palace.
title: An Interview with Christina Claypole. Conducted by Nadine Muller. 25 June 2017.

description: Maggie Goren’s grandfather, Lance Corporal Matthew Evans, died in the First World War, leaving behind his wife, Annie, who was pregnant with their fourth child. Maggie talks about her father’s experience growing up the son of a widow, and about the financial, educational and emotional repercussions of his father’s death. Maggie reflects on the intergenerational effects of bereavement and shares some of her writings about war.
title: An Interview with Maggie Goren. Conducted by Nadine Muller. 5 June 2017.

description: Brenda Hillman and her husband Terry, who was a pilot, were living on a service base in Malaya, when Terry was killed in a helicopter crash, leaving Brenda with their eighteen-month old son. Brenda describes the challenges of returning to the UK, returning to teaching to earn a living and the support she received from family members. She also talks about her mother’s widowhood and remembers her father who was killed in an air-raid in West Malling.
title: An Interview with Brenda Hillman. Conducted by Nadine Muller. 13 May 2017.

description: Mary Moreland is from Kilkeel, Co. Down in Northern Ireland. Her husband John served in the Ulster Defence Regiment in Northern Ireland during the Troubles and was killed in 1988. Mary is currently Chairwoman of the War Widows’ Association. Mary talks about the circumstances of John’s death, breaking the news to her children, her own experience of serving in the UDR, the experience of being a widow in Northern Ireland during the Troubles, developing her career, and her role within the War Widows’ Association.
tag_list: "War Widows' Association of Great Britain" "Heritage Lottery Fund" "war widowhood" "war widows" "oral history" "history of war" "women and war" remembrance "Liverpool John Moores University"
title: An Interview with Mary Moreland. Conducted by Ailbhe McDaid. 23 June 2017.

description: Wendy Hutchinson was born in Kent and met her husband Tony in 1987, when he was a serving member of the Territorial Army. Wendy talks about their busy family life with seven children and details how Tony left the army in 1992. She describes Tony’s experience of Post- Traumatic Stress Disorder, and outlines the lack of support Tony and Wendy received before Tony’s death by suicide in 2015.
title: An Interview with Wendy Hutchinson. Conducted by Ailbhe McDaid. 28 April 2017.

description: Denise Haddon’s father, Ronald King, was killed in Malaya in 1942, when Denise was an infant. She tells the story of her parents’ relationship and describes life for her mother, Elizabeth Cooper, as a widow. Denise details the hectic early years of the war which her mother spent in Ireland before returning to Hounslow in 1947 where Denise was raised by her mother, grandmother and aunt. Denise talks about travelling to Singapore to visit her father’s grave in Kranji Cemetary, and about the implications of losing her father as a baby.
title: An Interview with Denise Haddon. Conducted by Clare Baybutt. 28 April 2017.

description: Christiane Kirton's husband, John, was killed when the submarine HMS Olympus was blown up in Malta in 1942 and Christiane was just 21. She describes her early life, her work in domestic service, and her financial difficulties bringing up two children on her own. She talks about moving from South Shields to Doncaster during the war, struggling to make ends meet and her pride in her children and grandchildren.
title: An Interview with Christiane Kirton. Conducted by Nadine Muller. 25 June 2017.

description: Rita Armin’s husband Henry served in the British Army during the Second World War. He sustained severe injuries after a botched parachute jump, leaving him disabled for the rest of his life. He died in 1998. Rita describes how she met Henry and their happy marriage, including the birth of their son Philip. She outlines the struggles to receive financial and practical support while Henry was alive. Rita talks about her successful career working for British Airways, her current role as an award-winning Police Service Volunteer, and her love of travel.
tag_list: "war widows" "Heritage Lottery Fund" "Liverpool John Moores University" "War Widows' Association of Great Britain" "British Army" "British Airways" "Second World War" "Tom Hanks"
title: An Interview with Rita Armin. Conducted by Ailbhe McDaid. 27 February 2017.

description:
If it sounds bluegrass, that's what it is... (Dunmore East and all that.)

The birth of this demo collaboration with Eelco Beckers "Goin' Down Smokin" was scribbled together in a room at the Ronald MacDonald House in Crumlin Hospital(for sick children)Dublin, while waiting for Eelco's son Josh, to recover from one of his many surgeries.
Josh is now ten with a lot of promise...just like the song!

I write the words I sing the song
While Eelco strings the melody / and plays the gift of harmony
That's how the songs get done!

GOIN' DOWN SMOKIN'

Billy banker's boy lived high up on the hill
with the devil and a silver spoon
take what he could get when the waters were still
from the cabin out at Miller's lagoon
Cabin it was small just a kitchen and a bed
but it didn't bother Billy boy none
Took what he could get the night wind said
Sally with the red dress on.

Mama trimmed her hem an inch above the knee
saying Sally be a good girl try
There's a lot of crazy people in the world today
not to mention Billy banker's boy.
Creep up like a vine to her cabin door
Mama never saw the tears she cried
Pulled a .44 from the dresser drawer
the night that Billy Banker's boy died.

Chorus
Someone's goin' down smokin' by the light of the moon
Someone's taking the fall now don't you know that's true
There's a pistol at the bottom of old miller's lagoon
There's a broken body Sally's red dress too.

Sally's red dress lay on the kitchen floor 
while the boy lay cold in her bed
Called her lovin' Mama in the middle of the night
said the son of a rich man's dead
Mama held her baby in the rain down-pour
saying Sally go gather your things
there's a Greyhound leaving on the dot of four
don't you see it was you or him.

Chorus.
title: Goin' Down Smokin'

description:
Some write to poetic verse, some to the rhythm of the beat, and some to both. I used to say I could write lyrics about two flies buzzing up a wall if I had a good enough excuse, well this demo I tried with Eelco Beckers who came up with the title "That Little Word Called No"...gave me such an excuse, from there we built the song (mics left open with the intention to finish another day)he wrote the notes and played the melody while giving me the inspiration to write the words and sing the song... My first blast at Jazz... thanks Eelco.

THAT LITTLE WORD CALLED NO

Joe swaggers with a trilby on the upbeat side of town
Good-Time-Charlie looking for the perfect tease
Your lover struts the boards with a hundred different whores
and a bottle of your finest if you please.
The champagne overflows but he's always in control
Havana lingers warmly on his lip
Temptress burning slow long and lean and all aglow
another kiss placed hotly on that silky tip.

Chorus
And if you hear him asking for the Queen of hooker Street
Could a cut be in the deck for Smoky-Joe.
Slide him to your doorway let him feel your body heat
Whisper that little word called no.

His suit looks razor sharp as he shuffles through the deck
while the sax suggests you dance to Lilly's tune
Throw the Queen or throw the Knave doesn't matter which you save
there all cheaters in Havana's smoky room.

(chorus)

There's a joker up his sleeve still he's holding back the Ace
he understands the game but nothings free
Win or lose he'll pay there's a final hand to play
La Madame will never waver on the fee.

Chorus etc.
title: That Little Word Called No

description:
BIDEN/HARRIS... THERE'S A YOUNG DOVE AND AN EAGLE LEARNING ONCE AGAIN TO FLY!...Once upon a time I believed in the American dream; the last four years of Trump some how stole that dream...but today in this edit, on 7th. November 2020 with the Biden/Harris victory, I feel the very same sentiment in these inclusive lyric lines, when I first wrote this song as Barack Obama became President of the United States...                                         BLACK LIVES MATTER!...WHITE LIVES MATTER!..ALL LIVES MATTER!...                                      HOPEFULLY NOW AMERICA CAN BREATH AGAIN!              

THERE'S A TEAR IN JESSIE'S EYE

There's a tear in Jessie's eye as he remembers how it was
There's a gladness in his heart that wins tonight
There is thunder in the room Lord it's ringing with applause
There's no colour through the tears of black or white.
There are memories in chains disappearing in the wind
And a wave that lifts you higher than the flow
For tonight will be remembered like no other night has been
As our troubled winds of hope begin to blow.

Chorus
Blow you winds of change through the mind of culture's chains
Come steady wind that keeps you sailing high
Underneath your umbrella no one feels the powering rain
Yet feels when there's a tear in Jessie's eye.

Change has been a long time coming and a God still on our side
There's a bridge to cross a mountain still to climb
Winds of hope through cotton blow across rivers deep and wide
And a peace deep in my bones for better times.

Chorus: (plus additional lines to end)
Don't you understand the meaning or the why
There's a young dove and an eagle learning once again to fly
Know the reason there's a tear in Jessie's eye.
title: There's A Tear In Jessie's Eye

description:
A SMILE CAN DO IT!

Although Sophie the shop girl had nothing to gain, when a surprised customer discovered he had a lotto win of €600... her excitement and happiness for the winner was infectious... her smile the brightest rainbow on a cloudy day. Sophie reminded me of an old unfinished song I started some years ago, and the reason I wrote it in the first place.
There are dark days we all get now and then (some more than others)and most of the time nobody wants to hear about them, but sometimes there are the Sophie's with their smile that unwittingly show us what a wonderful gift it is to be happy for yourself and somebody else...thank you Sophie!...
Now I can hear staccato on the bridge of an old violin, and an angel of mercy sing in the chorus (maybe you can hear it too).

WEAR A SMILE FROM TIME TO TIME 
(from the "Bare Bones Collection"unfinished)

Sweet dreams don't fly in a dark and clouded sky
The world don't sigh as tears go running by
Remember when you cry you cry and cry alone
Your glowing smile makes it worth the while
You still got style when the world goes wild
The laughing child tears have never known
Laughing child never ever on your own.

When you fly the whole world wants to share that feeling
Block out the blackjack blues the future will be fine
Who needs to know when dark clouds they come stealing?
There are dark clouds on the edge of every dreamers mind.

Jane across the street sees the John she'd like to meet
She's acting so discreet he's planning on deceit
Both thinking on their feet lust pays a heavy toll
Hearts beat nine to five working hard to stay alive
Honey in the hive some manage to survive
And still the Jane's get by let the good times roll
Always there's a John and a pleading bleeding soul.

When you fly the whole world wants to share that feeling
block out the blackjack blues the future will be fine
Who needs to know when dark clouds they come stealing?
The John's all pay their dues further down the line
Be just you and wear a smile from time to time.
title: Wear A Smile From Time To Time

description:
This Demo track (which still needs a box player, some harmonies etc.)... The Ballad of Tom Crean's final voyage to Antarctica in 1914 aboard the ill-fated "Endurance" is one of a remarkable man, of unbelievable hardship and humility, and his unyielding courage gave me the inspiration to write this song a few years ago, after I read Michael Smith's book "An Unsung Hero". Driven by the frustration that it has taken 100 years to honour a farmers son who sailed with Scott and Shackleton and who became an integral part of their ambitious expeditions to the Antarctic, without any great honour ever bestowed upon him.
His return to a troubled and embittered Ireland and the quite Kerry village of Anascaul, without fuss or ceremony, filled me with bitter sweet admiration and sadness in equal measure. 

TOM CREAN HAUL ALONG

Slipped away on the Thames as the world went to war
Endurance set sail to a lonesome refrain
Old hand to the mast anchor heave away cast
To battle once more without favour or gain
Fare thee well Anascaul there's a tide on the rise
Berth for a sailor returned to the land
No plough to hold firm rigging set bough to stern
Slan go foil as the sails catch the wind

As the guns were ablaze on the Western front
How you fought through that long mid-day night
There you bent with your spine to the treacherous storm
Every muscle and bone crippled beaten and torn
Yet time for a song when the hauling was done
Scorned the wish you had never been born
Haul along the ice man haul along haul along

Eight hundred mile rise as the snow capped their eyes
Winds of wrath sliced a path to the marrow of some
Cold sea lashed and seared skin and bone the James Caird
South Georgia appeared on the tip of a thumb
There you hauled her bleak peaks with all hell in retreat
Stromness like a Rowan's welcome bloom on the lea
In the arms of white blossom no hero forgotten
For home is the sailor come home from the sea

Had Jesus forsaken your Anascaul son
While Shackleton praised the ice hero unsung
Weep the heart where old wounds stem the dream
Hear Antarctica sing with the ghost of Tom Crean
In a place where old hero's forever live on
Haul along the ice man haul along haul along
Haul along the ice man haul along haul along
title: Tom Crean Haul Along

description:
Who cares about one small step forward for one man with an unfinished song / or a giant leap backward for mankind with a drag-line and harpoon? 
THEIR KILLING WHALES AGAIN! burning the rain forests, filling the seas and the skies with pollutants, and destroying this beautiful planet! 
For three decades whale hunting has been outlawed... now in 2019 the laws have changed, allowing the factory ships to hunt and slaughter with impunity regardless of a world crammed with knowledge, research warnings, and technology at its finger tips.
Although this song is about the plight of "The Great Whale" it represents every living creature on this planet, especially the ones that are hunted and killed to near extinction by man, through Ignorance, Greed, Superstition, and Trophy Vanity.

THE GREAT WHALE SONG (Unfinished demo track)

Set a course from the North to the East
Watch the sunrise creep over the bow
Let the wind in the sails go blowing
Salt ore' your lips and your brow
The smell of the sea fill your senses
The lapping swell round the bark
Her song I hear out on the water
Sweet as the meadowy lark

Waltz in her garden of sapphire and blue
See her rise in a heavenly arc
Fan the great tail of freedom
Along mainsail quarters and spar
Sail we in all mystery of starlight
Old fishermen easy and slow
Hear my great Queen of the ocean
Sing deep in her waters below

Chorus
Don't hunt the great whale burn the tilly lamp oil
Don't prime the harpoon for the killing
Don't slice her and bleed her dear God you don't to
Must the blood of mankind keep spilling
For the dollar the yen and the shilling

Though hunted and prized for her glory
There she blows on the old starboard side
A creature of grace and great wonder
No mariners kin can deny 
No cannon to fire death and sadness
No spyglass to rally the kill
Her song will be heard down the ages
'Till the ages are wasted and still...
Chorus. Hear the call of the great whale singing(END)
title: The Great Whale Song/ Demo

description:
I was a fourteen year old runaway on Tottenham Court Road.
Hungry and sick when I met Christina, a "Working Girl, more accustomed to nightlife, red lights, black leather and lecherous leers, than taking care of a skinny Irish kid who lost his way to Camden town... she took me by the hand and saved my life.
I have never forgotten her kindness or that other side off her life where loneliness and desperation pave a different path.
I wrote this song with Christina in mind.

Every book has its' secret cover every street its' darkened door
From every beam a shadow falls and lights go down once  more.

AS THE LIGHTS GO DOWN.  (for Christina)

You tell me when you're lonely 
While you dance without music or sound
You tell me when your iced glass is dry 
As your world comes tumbling down
You try to hide your sweet body
In a tight low dress that you found
On the floor of Marilyn's closet
Long before the lights go down.

Here the landlord calls last orders
But the sinners don't want to go home
And the women keep on dancing inhibitions lost and gone
All the men they go half crazy every one a lost Cathy's clown
No one stays to dry the tear drops as the lights go down.

There's a hand beneath another 
There's a slipper filled up with red wine
Soft shadows in a room old and dim 
Where two bodies embrace and entwine
It will be this way 'till eternity
Nothing changes whatever you found
As you feel another's slow teardrop
As the lights they all go down.

(repeat chorus) +
Could this be hell or heaven... as the lights go down.
title: As The Lights Go Down

description:
Pieta House... a place of refuge and mending, is there for all of the silent ones who believe they are alone in their world of darkness and despair.
Tilly Thompson was one, who experienced a dark lonely place, and although many years have passed since we met, her beauty and sadness has never left my thoughts.
She, and so many like her, gave me the inspiration to write this song.
Thank you Pieta House, for being there with comfort and understanding, for all the lost and found Tilly Thompsons of this world.

THE BALLAD OF TILLY THOMPSON 
(This is 1 of 13 original tracks taken from my debut album "Storylines")

Pick a rose mind the thorn she softly said
Her heart's been sold and bought
Cuckoo sleeping in her cot
Loves sweet dreams were torn and fraught
With a torn deep in the wound of the unwed
Tilly Thompson sleeps forever in your head.
Many years ago we sat outside the door
She was pale petit and blond
When they pulled her from the pond
Younger than her years no lesson learned
Older now and the days are keeping score
Just like they did a thousand times before

In the hall of locks and keys I hear her crying
Bloody bracelet on her wrist 
Show the path where death has kissed
Her appointment was three or was it four
Tilly Thompson can't remember anymore.

No confetti ever touched her golden hair
Lace and silk caressed her thigh
But the moment passed her by
Was it just another tragedy or lie
Reaching out for love, love wasn't there
Just ten again when they strapped her to a chair.
They asked her if she'd like to keep her clothes
Still they put them in a box
Turned the key and sealed the locks
As she stood there naked in her socks
Time to take the med it's best doctor knows
Sleeping with the cuckoo thorn and rose.
Chorus
As she walks the long and sleepless corridor
Tilly Thompson can't remember anymore.
title: The Ballad of Tilly Thompson

description:
This unfinished demo recording was inspired by the work of Dutch artist Vincent Van Gough and a boy named Josh.
His mother is from Tipperary Ireland, his father The Netherlands ...
Josh spent the first year of his life in Crumlin hospital Dublin for sick children and this gave me reason to often visit and witness the great courage in such little warriors like josh and the monumental care given by nurses and staff at Crumlin... hence... Colours for Josh. 
One day it will be complete with harmonies and all?
 
COLOURS FOR JOSH
Beat a green and purple drum hear a ra ta ta ta tat.
Pick a pot of Newton colours stroke a sable
Pallet mixed upon the wind coloured circles without end
With a sunflower and a blue chair by the table
On a moonlit cobalt night see the black cat on the tiles
As red and yellow waltz with amber's glow
Shadows kissed by dark & light dance beneath the lantern bright
As a symphony of colours start to flow

Chorus
Rock a by my little man dreamy head close your eyes
Hear the nightingales of Crumlin sing your song
Let the colours of old Vincent whisper soft a lullaby
Little drummer paint the music with your drum
Lay your pallet down 'till morning comes along

On the wall above your cot hangs the bridge at Langlois
Swirling colours mingle boldly in the wash
Young girls dip their daily clothes colours sing while to and fro
There's a slow hand rocks the cradle baby Josh
When you grow as dreamers do let the colours paint your path
Let the music take you out to Vincent's stars
Ochre tan and turquoise blue will be waiting there for you
With a thousand songs and a rainbow in a jar.

Chorus
title: 03 Colours For Josh (Demo)

description:
Michael Power: The first Catholic Bishop of Toronto, and only son of William Power "Master Sailor" who sailed out from Co. Waterford in the early 1800's and settled in Novo Scotia;
became the driving force behind the men and women who cared for  the Irish Emigrants, as they poured off the coffin ships and into the famine sheds of Toronto. 
He was stricken by typhus and died at 43 while caring for the sick and dying.
Today he is remembered with honour among Canada's Irish diaspora, but almost unheard of in the shame corridors of Irish History. 
(also on youtube Finbarr O' Reilly  'To Be Of Irelands Famine')




THE BALLAD OF MICHAEL POWER.
The famine ships made ready  at each harbour port and dock
with a cargo of despair they sailed away
Leave old Erin's shore with worn lapel ragged frock
dreaming only of the sunrise out along Toronto bay
Bitter days of grief and sorrow raging seas to count the dead
no mercy for the weak out on the deep
On the quay one solemn soul wringing hands bowing head
forty thousand broken hearts their dreams now in his keep.

And still we ask the question how such hunger could endure
So many starve while stores of grain were swelling at the door
Their bodies bent in two out of sight of well-to-do
And far away the taste of bitter sour
Lay on the tongue of Father Michael Power

As he stood at evenings tide witnessed hunger flood the docks
the famine ships lined out their wailing spars
Emigrant of skeletal sunken eyes matted locks
stole away his heart and soul like a million grieving stars
You may ask of your forefathers who lived on to tell the tale
when music died around the scented bower
Why the Maple gave a sailors son to walk with them they'll say
no greater love had any than Father Michael Power.

Chorus change.
And far away the angels claimed the hour 
candle burning bright at heavens open door 
Burn on for liberty the light of Michael Power.
title: Michael Power

description:
A Christmas verse...
Life is not always as it seems, and people living rough, and dying rough; once were beautiful, once had  families, lovers and sweethearts, stories to tell, and a safe place to lay their head... 
This poem tells the story of "Dorrie" a bag-lady I knew when I was a kid in Dublin. 
(The words have been slightly altered in an updated version, which does not affect the story line.)


DON'T YOU REMEMBER?

She leaned against the window frame, pressing her gloveless hand upon a lamp-lit golden gown, behind a frosted pane.
It was cold to the touch, yet in her kindled heart
memories and glowing embers.
As she dreamed on the weathered side of Christmas glass,
capturing a bronchial breath between the tears, snow began to fall, she never noticed. "Look Danny. Don't you remember?"

He sang her favourite song, then kissed her soft velvet lips.
She kissed him back as they went swirling 
through the heavens on a snow flakes dream, 
in old winters month of December.
"I was your princess as you danced me in your arms, 
and oh' how we danced, out beyond the Universe, 
me and you, my vagabond Prince".....
"Don't you see him dancing. Don't you remember.

They were better times then, when her sweetheart held
her gloveless hand, warmly in his. "Our hearts were on fire 
as we danced across the stars; 
me in a golden gown; you in all your splendour".
He was never one for putting by the pennies, believing not,
that the pounds would look after themselves. Pennies were for
spending, life was for living, and to age, he would not surrender.

It wasn't the cold black wind, brought tears to the edge 
of her red rimmed eyes, or near empty content 
of a screw-cap, in a brown paper bag, just by-gone tears, 
filched of emotion, they once could render.
No place for them to fall after his death. 
No alley or park bench gave comfort as the city streets, 
stole away the tears she wept, leaving the memory of sentiment edged in black. Returned to sender.

"I've never stopped loving you" she whispered. 
Closing her eyes in the glow of window-light display. 
The brown paper bag a sequinned purse in a pair of 
china-like hands, never again to feel the cold of winter.
Once again, he held her in his arms, soaring higher than the
Christmas heavens as familiar notes played out.
"listen the band, playing our song! Don't you remember Danny.
How we danced... Don't you remember?"
title: Don't You Remember

description:
Cherryfield Road in Dublin, was where Anne came from. 
The "Core" (Corps)a dance hall in Crumlin where we stumbled into each other, and Galway's Salthill where it all happened; so far back in the day.

CHERRYFIELD GIRL
You were there with the school day done
In a Cherry-field sunset no rules claimed the young
Generation was played by the band
As you held my heart in the palm of your hand.
We were there at the Core and in truth
The hurricane swept through the wild streets of youth
While the whirlwind it started the fire
And we blown away on the flames of desire.

That fire made our hearts want to soar want to fly
Like a bird in the mist of this fairy-tale world
In a moment forever that never passed by
The dreamer of dreams of dreams such dreams
And the Cherry-field girl.

When Cohen broke the rules with lyric and song
Stones rocked the world the force it goes on
Like the love that burns deep in my heart
How lucky we were to be there at the start.
Look at us as the years slide away
In Galway we danced as rock and roll played
And the camera it told not a lie
As it captured the dream in the wink of an eye.

That dream made our hearts want to soar want to fly etc..

No we never fit into a delicate frame
That polaroid print with its moment in time
In a box with its love and last chance
We opened it up and continue the dance.

That dance made our hearts want to soar want to fly
Like a bird in the mist of this fairy-tale world
With a moment forever that never passed by
In a picture with corners that curl 
See the dreamer of dreams of dreams such dreams
See the Cherry-field girl
My beautiful, beautiful, beautiful, Cherry-field girl.
title: CHERRYFIELD GIRL

description:
I wrote this Anti-war ballad which was Inspired by the story of child soldiers in Uganda and in particular the story of"China Ketetsi", who tirelessly continues to campaign worldwide with the support of people like, Woopie Goldberg, Bill Clinton, Robert De Niro and so many others.
When childhood is stolen, humanity suffers the deepest of all wounds.


MOZANDI RUN
I have written these troubled words 
for every child-soldier ever born
For peace and understanding in our world...
This song is named "Mozandi Run"

Mozandi comes to steal away the daybreak
Mozandi comes to blow away the sun, Mozandi comes.
Mozandi girl never knew her childhood
Mozandi knew the sound of beating drums, Mozandi Run. 

Throw away your combat boots, disengage your gun
Hurry towards your new day, run Mozandi Run.
Skip through mine and mortar, love each Mother's son
Caress each fallen daughter, run, Mozandi run.

Mozandi's heart hardened by the gunfire
Mozandi's dreams broken one by one, Mozandi run.
Mozandi runs to hide among the flowers
Mozandi waits to hear new footsteps come, Mozandi run.

Throw away your combat boots, disengage your gun
Hurry towards your new day, run Mozandi run.
Skip through mine and mortar, love each Mother's son
Caress each fallen daughter, run, Mozandi run.
Run Mozandi, run Mozandi, run Mozandi, run Mozandi run.
title: 01 Mozandi Run [High Quality]

description:
Je vois bien qu'il y a un déséquilibre. C'est surtout les hommes qui ont des comportements répréhensibles, moi inclus. Je le reconnais et j’investis une partie de mon temps à cette reconnaissance de ce qui se passe en moi, dans mes relations, mes erreurs, dans mes meilleurs coups, et j’agis en en réponse à ces observations. 

Mais j’aimerais ici utiliser une métaphore homme-femme non pas comme une histoire littérale mais comme manière de nommer les principes masculins et féminins, yin et yang, poissons et vierge que nous incarnons tous qu'on le veuille ou non.

UN HOMME AFFAMÉ, AVARE ET PUISSANT

Un homme affamé, avare et puissant décide de faire d’une femme sa femme. Il en abuse toute sa vie sans apprendre quoi que ce soit dans la lancée. Il souffre mais son momentum ne lui permet pas de reconnaitre cette souffrance, ni celle qu’il cause. Mais imaginez cette relation sur plusieurs générations. Éventuellement il apprend. Quelque chose change. 

Nous sommes en train d’apprendre. Le territoire que nous violons depuis plusieurs générations est en train de nous enseigner quelque chose. Écoutons-le.  

De vivre plus en syntonie avec nos corps, avec le territoire, avec l’eau qui circule dans ce corps et dans ce territoire va changer la mélodie de notre quotidien. Nos rythmes mentaux et corporels, ce que nous faisons de nous même d’un moment à l’autre va changer.

Tout va changer: le rituel de préparer des repas, de choisir d’où viennent nos aliments. Celui d’aller au gym, au studio de yoga, ou à l'aréna. La méditation qu’on trouve qui fonctionne pour nous, que ce soit dans la marche vers le bureau ou sur le coussin de méditation. Les conversation qui guérissent, que ce soit avec un ami, un enseignant sage, avec un psychologue ou un cercle de personnes qui ont un souci de notre vie. Tout va changer. 

Nous avons des rituels. Certains sont évidents. Certains le sont moins. Certains sont de toute évidence sains. Certains de toute évidence malsains. Les reconnaissons-nous? Pouvons-nous partager à ce sujet? Avons-nous des mécanismes de soutien en place pour mieux gérer nos habitudes?

J’un un feeling que depuis quelques générations le momentum s’est suffisamment atténué et nous pouvons cesser le viol. Nous pouvons commencer à demander pardon à cette femme, à ses grand-mères et ses grand-pères et nous pouvons commencer à reconnaitre nos habitudes, physiques, mentales et émotives et prendre de meilleures décisions, personnelles, familiales, communautaires et organisationnelles. 

Je vous invite à écouter cette entrevue de la CBC où l’on peut entendre des voix de gens pour qui cette expérience d’abus est inscrite dans le corps, et comment aujourd’hui, en 2018, on peut vivre ensemble bien au delà d’efforts politiques de réconciliation.
  

http://www.cbc.ca/radio/ideas/first-nation-second-nation-a-discussion-about-the-state-of-indigenous-people-in-canada-today-1.4489386
